metadata.name: Origin-a-tions I: Creation #119
metadata.description:
Everything has an origin. But for some things, we can't truly grasp where they origin-a-ted from. And for that, we pretend to prefer to enjoy things as they are, instead of trying to understand why they are.

Origin-a-tions is a three-parts series of generative artwork, starting with Part I: Creation, that depicts one possible variation of how things may be originating.

* * *

Press S to save as PNG.

Made by: yenren / twitter.com/yenrenART
Made with: JavaScript + HTML Canvas
License: LICENSE.txt

metadata.name: I wish for the metaverse ... #131
metadata.description:
I WISH FOR THE METAVERSE TO RINSE OFF OF ME is a collection about both the power and the infirmity of affirmations. Shamanic, mantra-like, willful, affirmations seek to map a desired direction. That is, until time and mind get in the way.¬† Within brief, passing moments, our minds are able to manifest conflicting wishes‚Äîand do so via declarative, convincing statements. 
¬†
This work plays inside the chasm that divides intention and action. If we don‚Äôt know what we want, how can we act? Without the commitment of mind along the vast¬†axis of time, our affirmations risk becoming sloganistic, simplistic, unrealistic‚Äîwavering proclamations that announce our vulnerability. 
¬†
Key words in these algorithmic affirmations shift over time to reflect the way our minds fluctuate. By shuffling words, this collection also explores our fluid relation to language. How to construct meaningful lives, when signification changes, moment to moment, within our minds? 
¬†
I WISH FOR THE METAVERSE TO RINSE OFF OF ME is a performance of fragility, which is where our humanity‚Äîand our beauty‚Äîabounds.

-return will resume the animation

metadata.name: Transmission #126
metadata.description:
GT by Ahmad Moussa || Gorilla Sun
Twitter -> @gorillasu

Notes on randomness and rarity:
This token generates a random permutation of a transmission. A transmission consists of a set of points (interceptors) that a diagonally spanned across the canvas, and connected with lines.
These interceptors can sometimes occur in a square shape.
Sometimes the signal fails to connect two dots, the amount of drops in these connections makes up the decomposition parameter.
The colored ligaments come in a variety of colors, and sometimes the entire transmission has a different color scheme. Some color schemes are extremely rare.

Notes on posting to Twitter:
To make Twitter display these correctly and not harshly compress them, they're best saved in the .jpg or .jpeg format and then posted.

metadata.name: Skyfloors #158
metadata.description:
Skyfloors are a study of perspective, occlusion, color, shape and motion. Occular meditation. A visceral demonstration of noise' ability to emulate natural systems; rolling hills, an angry sea, gentle breezes, crawling skin - all wrapped in 2d isometric projection with a flamboyant twist and a minimal nod to cel animation.

Controls:

right arrow - increase speed in direction 1
left arrow - increase speed in direction 0
P - pause / play
S - save image (increase res in devtools first if you are printing)
L - switch to black outline on brightlines featured pieces
B - switch to solid background on split background featured pieces
D - disable drop shadow

These pieces are pretty feature heavy and include a couple of ultra rare surprises.

All color palettes are procedurally generated, with each edition selecting for 1 of 4 different palette functions. 2 of these functions are open source and developed by meodai:
https://twitter.com/meodai
https://github.com/meodai

https://twitter.com/p4stoboy

metadata.name: The Arcimboldo Project #74
metadata.description:
A tribute to Giuseppe Arcimboldo (1526 - 1593), an Italian painter best known for creating imaginative portrait heads made entirely of objects such as fruits, vegetables and flowers.

This token is made of a combination of 192 layers (24 layers x 8 fruits/vegetables/flowers categories).
All the layers have been hand-painted in acrylics on paper and digitally composed.
The background has a random HSV color.

As always a big thank you goes to Koei Ural - @KoeiUral for the huge help with the p5.js code!

metadata.name: Phantoms #115
metadata.description:
Phantoms is a series of hazy memories of distant places. Some tranquil, others sinister, each scene is as much defined by what is revealed as by what remains unseen.

In this collection I aim to juxtapose hard and soft. Blocky shapes form the core of the compositions. Upon these surfaces, soft textures appear to flow and drip over the sides. Varying levels of opacity, lighting, and fog effects further soften the scenes to create an atmospheric, dream-like quality. By remaining semi-abstract, each of the color palettes are given the space to influence the mood dramatically.

metadata.name: blind vision (audio) #85
metadata.description:
- 40 very short stories of real people about being blind

- each one is written in braille (you can see it, but probably don't know how to read) 

- and the same story is recorded as audio, generated by synthetic voice-over (that will help)

- fingerprint on each picture touches braille text (that's how it usually works for braille)

- photos on the background are hardly readable (cause visual beauty is a small percentage of beauty)

- background sounds are manually recorded all over the world 

This media-mix can't be fully understood by both sides - by those who is blind nor by those who is sighted and that's the kind of a point.


*Sound launches by click. Next clicks multiply it.
For iOS - "silent mode" has to be turned off)
